# truthy checks are safer than undefined checks for optional state assignment

When conditionally assigning optional input values to state:

```typescript
// ❌ Type error — 'string | null' is not assignable to 'string'
if (action.input.field !== undefined) entry.field = action.input.field;

// ✅ Truthy check handles both null and undefined
if (action.input.field) state.field = action.input.field;

// ✅ For booleans, use explicit null/undefined checks
if (action.input.field !== undefined && action.input.field !== null)
  state.field = action.input.field;
```

The truthy check works because both `null` and `undefined` are falsy. For boolean fields, you cannot use truthy checks since `false` is also falsy — use explicit null/undefined guards instead.

Since [[nullable input types require explicit coalescing to match state types]], this pattern complements the `|| null` coalescing approach for different assignment scenarios.

